data.content:
Replace `[ExpectedException]` with `Assert.ThrowsExactly<T>`, which lets you inspect the exception and won't pass if an unrelated line throws:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void CreateUser_NullEmail_ThrowsException()
{
    var service = new UserService();

    var ex = Assert.ThrowsExactly<ArgumentNullException>(
        () => service.CreateUser(null, "John"));

    Assert.AreEqual("email", ex.ParamName); // bonus: verify the right param
}
```

**Why:**
- `[ExpectedException]` passes if *any* line throws — it can mask bugs in arrange/assert code.
- `Assert.ThrowsExactly<T>` scopes the check to the exact lambda and returns the exception so you can assert on its properties.
- Use `Assert.Throws<T>` instead if you want to match derived exception types too.
